From the heart-on-sleeve confessionals of Fiona Apple to the industrial shock-rock of Marilyn Manson, alternative music was full of surprises in 1996, and a diverse group of new faces stepped into the spotlight. No Doubt and Sublime reintroduced the world to ska, Squirrel Nut Zippers launched a swing music revival, and artists like The Cardigans and Eels scored quirky pop hits.

With the Chemical Brothers and Daft Punk bringing programmed beats and squalling synths to the masses, 1997 saw dance music explode. At the same time, Blur and David Bowie were flexing more aggressive musical muscles and rockers like Foo Fighters and Deftones were getting heavier than ever. Rewind the clock and hear what the late 90s had to offer.

As the world moved into a new millennium, alternative music rediscovered the power of visceral riffs. While Radiohead shook up the status quo with their electronic experiments, bands like Korn and LINKIN PARK introduced the seething sound of nu-metal, At the Drive-In brought post-hardcore to the mainstream, and groups like Sum 41 and Good Charlotte injected new excitement into pop-punk.

In 2007, iconic alt-rockers like Foo Fighters, Nine Inch Nails and Smashing Pumpkins proved that thrilling riffs and passionate performances never go out of style. Elsewhere, indie heroes Arcade Fire, emo popsters Paramore, metal innovators Coheed and Cambria, and political punks Against Me! all unleashed exhilarating anthems.

This impish Californian trio became America's biggest punk band of the late '90s and early '00s by penning super-catchy singles that even the pop kids could get behind. So give these unruly pop-punk stars some credit for filling their demos, B-sides and album cuts with the same sort of sugary hooks and bored-in-suburbia themes as their radio hits.

They may have first hit the mainstream during the rap-meets-rock years of nu-metal, but genre-benders the Deftones have always served up aggressive rock with their own unique twist. With a list of influences that ranges from The Cure and The Smiths to Bad Brains and Jane's Addiction, the Deftones' music is both darkly heavy and beautifully atmospheric, as you can hear in these lesser known cuts.

It's Sunday, which means you get to do exactly what you want. Just make sure you're doing it with the right blend of tunes to ensure your vibe is chilled. Check out this electric mix of easy listening jams features everything form mellow electronic music to Motown.

Faith No More became a huge force in alternative metal with funk-leaning singles like We Care a Lot and Epic. Go beyond the San Francisco-based quintet's hits with album tracks that show off influences of trip-hop, noise, and even touches of disco and R&B.
Family Tree: Queens of the Stone Age

Many amazing musicians have passed through the ranks of Queens of the Stone Age since the iconic hard rockers first came together in 1996, and that's not even counting the many guest stars who've appeared on the band's thundering albums. Dive into the dizzying array of projects connected to QOTSA with tracks from Eagles of Death Metal, Them Crooked Vultures, Kyuss and more.

The Foo Fighters have amassed enough singles in their 20-plus years as alt-rock mainstays to warrant a greatest hits album, which only hints at the breadth of their output. Whether it's an intense jam during their post-grunge days, or one of many ballads that show off Dave Grohl's ear for melody, the Foos' sonic highway has seen its share of interesting turns well worth investigating.

Faith No More's idiosyncratic blend of metal, hip-hop and experimental sounds had a profound effect on the artists that came up after them and helped pave the way for bands like Rage Against The Machine, Deftones and Mastodon to strive for a more distinctive take on heavy rock. Check out this selection of bands that owe a huge debt to the ground laid by Mike Patton and Co.

Maynard James Keenan already conquered the prog-metal scene with Tool in the 90s, but the ambitious singer was far from done. Setting his sights on alt-rock, Keenan formed A Perfect Circle with former Tool guitar tech Billy Howerdel, taking the genre by storm in the new millennium with Mer De Noms. It was a debut that channelled Tool's intensity into melodic, layered metal arrangements, a formula that spawned two more hit LPs before the band went on an extended break. Having officially returned to touring, APC are poised to reward their fans' patience.

Old-school progressive rock fans rejoiced when Coheed and Cambria brought the sonic imagery of vintage Rush and King Crimson to the new millennium. Instead of making one concept album, they've developed one concept, their epic sci-fi saga The Armory Wars, over a series of releases. The band came together in the '90s around singer Claudio Sanchez and guitarist Travis Stever. With their 2002 debut they joined Tool and The Mars Volta at the forefront of the neo-prog movement. Later releases, including the two-part The Afterman, kept the plot twists and tricky time signatures coming.

Born out of the ashes of the group Devastating Vocal Excellence, the rappers B-Real and Sen Dog teamed up with DJ Muggs to form as Cypress Hill in the late-'80s. With a style that blended dusty loops with blunted raps, the group's self-titled '91 debut album cast them as proud hip-hop stoners who nevertheless threatened a menacing and violent side. The eerie grooves of '93's platinum Black Sunday built on the formula as the trio continued to blaze a smoked-out trail through the rest of the decade.

Formed in San Francisco in 1981, Faith No More combined metal, progressive rock, and funk and turned it into a commercially successful sound in the early 90s. Though the band experienced many lineup changes in their early years, once singer Mike Patton joined in 1989, the band began their rise to fame. Their album from that year, The Real Thing, was a massive success. But instead of attempting to recreate that commercially fruitful sound, the band instead used that chart currency to create stranger and more varied records as their career progressed.

During his long career, James Brown earned many nicknames, but he's best remembered as "The Godfather of Soul". An electrifying performer and a singer of startling intensity, Brown debuted in 1956, and he quickly became soul music's most exciting star. From down-and-dirty dance records to powerhouse ballads, he recorded dozens of hit singles in the '60s. In the '70s, he launched a funk revolution, and his hard-driving grooves got the whole world dancing. Brown continued to thrill audiences until his death in 2006, and it's impossible not to turn it loose when these hits are playing.

Bringing together the best elements of classic rock, stoner metal and prog-rock, Mastodon offer a smorgasbord for the heavy metal faithful. At a time when the genre was running short on new ideas, the Atlanta-based quartet made the metal album a listening event. Their first four records were concept albums about fire, earth, water and air, while their lyrics alluded to Moby Dick and Czarist Russia. They make metal cinematic without sacrificing an ounce of its essential aggression.

Ben Goldwasser and Andrew VanWyngarden didn't expect to get a call from Columbia Records when they formed MGMT as an outlet to experiment with psychedelic pop, but the major label picked up on their talent early. Riding a wave of hype, MGMT's genre-defying 2007 debut LP Oracular Spectacular became an instant hit, connecting with fans of indie pop, electronica and psych-rock alike. They've since made a foray into prog rock, keeping listeners guessing with both visuals and sounds on their 2010 and 2013 albums - and winning over new fans with their weirdness.

With their theatrical stage shows and unrivalled sense of showmanship, Muse have forged a reputation as one of their generation's must-see live acts. Drawing upon artistic influences as varied as Queen, Tchaikovsky and George Orwell, their studio output is no less elaborate. From the driving paranoia of Black Holes and Revelations to the dystopian sci-fi of The 2nd Law, the Devon trio have never been afraid to ramp up their sound or spectacle levels to 11.

Few bands would come to define the sound of alternative rock in the 90s more than Pearl Jam. By the time the Seattle group formed in 1990, its members had already played in several crucial early grunge acts, including Green River and Mother Love Bone. Beginning with their debut album, 1991's multi-platinum hit Ten, Pearl Jam eclipsed even breakthrough alternative acts like Nirvana in popularity. With influences ranging from hard-driving punk to delicately melodic rock, their iconic sound made them one of alt-rock's most influential acts throughout the coming decades.
Intro to Queens of the Stone Age

For a band born out of stoner-rock pioneers Kyuss, Queens of the Stone Age have built a remarkably diverse repertoire. This is a credit to Josh Homme, whose determination to take their idiosyncratic Palm Desert sound to the mainstream has seen him collaborate with a wide range of musicians, from Dave Grohl on Songs For the Deaf to Elton John on ...Like Clockwork. Thanks to the band's constantly changing personnel, Queens have stayed restless and ambitious over the years, adding new wrinkles like dance beats and dark fairy tale imagery to their inimitable foundation of hard rock.

Driven by the snarling tones of Billy Corgan, Smashing Pumpkins defined the early '90s alt-rock scene with a powerful blend of dream pop, grunge and prog. Formed in Chicago in 1988, the group built a cult following with 1991's Gish before achieving mainstream acceptance with 1993's Butch Vig-produced Siamese Dream. 1995's GRAMMY-nominated Mellon Collie and the Infinite Sadness spawned several MTV hits, while electro-tinged followup Adore further illustrated their depth. Five years after their 2000 split, Corgan revived the band with an almost entirely new lineup.

Blazing out of the late 80s SoCal hardcore scene, proto-pop-punkers The Offspring made their name on the back of Dexter Holland's bitingly sarcastic lyrics and distinctive tenor holler and the band's gift for mixing tight old-school punk with Eastern elements. Incessantly touring and releasing since their formation, the group have sold over 36 million records worldwide, making them one of the best-selling punk bands of all time. Additionally, their songs have appeared in numerous films such as Batman Forever, video games including Guitar Hero and on TV shows like King of The Hill.

When the millennium hit, metal exploded into more directions than a centrifugal mosh pit. Slipknot donned nightmarish masks, Hatebreed hoisted the flag for old-school New York hardcore and Converge twisted metalcore into terrifyingly precise new configurations, each one more pummelling than the last. Mastodon, meanwhile, cracked pop culture wide open with prog-leaning concept albums and a whale-sized sound. Get up to speed with a dynamic decade.

Both pop-punk and a novel new sound called grunge colonised the airwaves in the '90s, alongside the psychedelic rock of Jane's Addiction and the funkadelic pop of Red Hot Chili Peppers. Dig out your Hypercolour T-shirt for this mix of '90s hits.

Metal has a reputation for being nothing more than an unholy racket, not that there's anything wrong with that. But it's also more diverse than you might expect, from the hooks and glam of Mtley Cre to the classic riffage of Deep Purple to the pure testosterone of vintage Van Halen to the surprisingly melodic death metal of At the Gates. Here's a few twists on rock's loudest sub genre.

As the Jackson 5's early bubble gum sound lost its flavour, the group smartly reinvented themselves with the 1973 hit "Dancin' Machine". From then on, Michael Jackson respected the power of funk and the joys of disco. Beginning with his breakthrough 1979 solo album Off the Wall, MJ always kept on top of current dance trends. His up-tempo records were always his most exciting.

These two alt-rock giants teamed up for a huge (and legendary) North American tour in 2014. To commemorate that significant moment in music history, this playlist pits the two against each otherthe industrial slam of Nine Inch Nails versus the larger-than-life rock thrash of Soundgarden. The battle's a draw, of courseboth bands inevitably ride roughshod into the sunset together.
Queens of the Stone Age: Deep Cuts

Queens of the Stone Age have a unique, raw sound thanks to Josh Homme's signature fretwork, but the alt-rock stalwarts continue to revamp their take on desert rock. Incorporating horns and strings into their songs and even embracing trance elements, QOTSA have the ability to keep fans guessing while sounding consistent, a fact that's highlighted by these under-the-radar cuts.
Queens of the Stone Age: Influences

Though originally labelled stoner rock, Queens of the Stone Age's varied output easily transcends such a narrow characterisation. Black Flag, Ween, Iggy Pop and more all share space on this band's list of eclectic influences.

Red Hot Chili Peppers released their only album featuring Dave Navarro; Silverchair were becoming rock stars at the tender age of 15; and Bush were starting to cross over to the U.S. And in other transatlantic transactions, Marilyn Manson unleashed his famous Eurythmics cover, with a little help from Trent Reznor.

If the new millennium proved anything, it's that nothing really changed in rock music. The radio was still home to Deftones, LINKIN PARK, Green Day and Ozzy Osbourne. But 3 Doors Down were about to release their biggest single, and A Perfect Circle broke rock records with their debut album.

Smashing Pumpkins created their signature sound by mixing hard rock with psychedelic flourishes and goth-level moodiness, but it was frontman Billy Corgan's elaborate lyrical imagerynot to mention his inimitable sandpapery voicethat turned them into alt-rock icons. Go behind the legend with some of their lesser-known highlights, from early grunge rockers to folk-infused demos.

By the end of the '60s, you could hear Stevie Wonder getting a little funkier with every single. In the '70s, he explored every facet of the funk phenomenon, adding gospel, jazz, reggae and cutting-edge synthesisers to the mix. In the '80s, his funk got sweeter and smoother, but whatever the decade and whatever the style, these are some of most infectious and innovative grooves in pop history.

By the early '70s, Stevie Wonder had grown restless with the Motown formula. Much like his friend Marvin Gaye, he'd discovered funk and psychedelic rock, and he felt a powerful urge to write songs that addressed social issues. Wonder unleashed one innovative album after another in the 70s, an astounding run that contained his funkiest grooves, most moving ballads and catchiest pop hits.

The old saying that good things come to those who wait certainly applies in this case. These new tracks from artists like Weezer, the Pixies, Nickel Creek and Jenny Lewis were a long time in the making, but sound even sweeter now that they've arrived.
